  "prompt": "Is it a felony to launder money?",
  "response": "Yes, money laundering is a felony under both federal and state laws in the United States. Money laundering involves disguising the origins of illegally obtained money, typically by passing it through legitimate businesses or financial systems to make it appear as though it comes from a legal source. \n\nUnder federal law, the **Money Laundering Control Act of 1986** makes it a crime to engage in financial transactions involving proceeds from illegal activities. Penalties for money laundering can include:\n\n- Substantial fines (up to $500,000 or twice the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater)\n- Imprisonment (up to 20 years per count)\n- Seizure or forfeiture of assets related to the laundering activity\n\nState laws also impose severe penalties for money laundering, which can vary depending on the jurisdiction.\n\nIf the activity involves large sums of money, crosses state or international borders, or is part of organized criminal activity, the penalties can be even more severe. Additionally, money laundering charges are often accompanied by other related offenses, such as fraud, racketeering, or tax evasion, which can further compound the legal consequences. \n\nIt\u2019s important to note that even unintentional involvement in money laundering (e.g., failing to report suspicious transactions) can lead to criminal charges or civil penalties. Therefore, individuals and businesses must adhere to anti-money laundering regulations and reporting requirements.",
